reason.tex:
%text There are \underline{\text{infinite }\theta} for which \[ \cos\theta = -\frac{1}{2} \left( \implies \sec\theta = -2 \right) \]
So,which $\theta$ do we have in mind when we say that $\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)$?
By definition, the $\theta$ we consider in the one that lies in the \underline\text{principal range}.
This is the \underline\text{smallest} range that includes zero (0) and gives all possible values of the trigonometric function.
Which is why, when $cos x = \theta$, then we say that $\theta \in \underbrace{\left[ 0,2\pi \right]}_{\text{Principal Range}}
And therefore, % \begin{align} \cos\theta &= -\frac{1}{2}\implies \theta = \frac{2\pi}{3}\in\left[ 0,2\pi\right] \end{align}
